NBA Spin
--------

There was a very curiously headlined piece in the Wall Street Journal last =
week: How the NBA Plans to Remake TV Deals and Net Billions of Dollars for =
Its Stars ( https://www.wsj.com/business/media/how-the-nba-plans-to-remake-=
its-tv-deals-and-score-billions-for-its-stars-32678182 ). Sounds like good =
news for the NBA, right? Not so much, methinks.

The stars of the National Basketball Association are taking to the court as=
 a new season begins next week. Behind the scenes, the league has started t=
alks to secure the billions of dollars in media-rights fees that will help =
pay their huge salaries.

As the NBA enters its first media negotiations in a decade, its biggest par=
tners, Disney=E2=80=99s ESPN and Warner Bros. Discovery=E2=80=99s TNT =E2=
=80=94 which together pay about $2.6 billion a year =E2=80=94 aren=E2=80=99=
t looking to pony up big spending increases. Each company is under investor=
 pressure to trim costs, with cable TV=E2=80=99s decline and hefty mergers =
weighing on their balance sheets. Meanwhile, the largest sports broadcaster=
 in local markets is in bankruptcy and on the brink of liquidation.

The solution: The league is looking to bring additional parties to the nego=
tiating table as it plots out its new deals, which would go into effect aft=
er the 2024-2025 season. For consumers, those deals could change significan=
tly where games are broadcast. ESPN and TNT, which carry roughly 165 nation=
ally televised games combined, are exploring signing up for smaller package=
s, said people familiar with the situation. That arrangement would help the=
m hang onto a premier asset in American media without breaking the bank. Th=
ose companies already are in renewal talks with the NBA, with an exclusive =
negotiation period set to expire in April.

This is bad news! The last time the NBA=E2=80=99s media rights were up for =
negotiation they never reached the open market because ESPN and TNT re-uppe=
d during their exclusive negotiating period; the primary news in this artic=
le is that neither network is willing to match the NBA=E2=80=99s desired pr=
ice. And what is that price?

In the American sports landscape, the National Football League towers above=
 all else. But the NBA is number two, given its appeal with younger audienc=
es, and is in a strong position to demand a tripling of fees, as it did las=
t time around, said David Levy, who negotiated TNT=E2=80=99s last deal with=
 the NBA in 2014. =E2=80=9CPop culture, fashion, relevancy=E2=80=94why woul=
dn=E2=80=99t the number 2 get a 3x increase?=E2=80=9D Levy said.

The NBA hasn=E2=80=99t said publicly what fee increase it is seeking. Tripl=
ing the last agreement would mean a deal worth about $78 billion over a dec=
ade. Media rights make up a big chunk of league revenues, along with ticket=
 and merchandise sales.=E2=80=99

The NBA may not have said it wants to triple its right fee publicly, but th=
at is the number that has been leaked for years now, and the expectation wi=
thin the league is for a substantial increase. The problem, though, was lai=
d out in the section above: ESPN, the preeminent sports network, is doing w=
ell to eke out a 2% revenue increase, and a 2% increase is a lot less than =
a 300% increase! In fact, an increase of this size would have wiped out all=
 but around $250 million of ESPN=E2=80=99s profit last year. It=E2=80=99s n=
ot going to happen.

The spin in the article, of course, is that tech is going to come to the re=
scue; Apple and Amazon are the two names mentioned, and in the past week th=
ere have been another raft of leaks pointing to Amazon specifically as a bi=
dder. From Front Office Sports ( https://frontofficesports.com/amazon-is-ey=
eing-an-nba-package-for-tuesdays-or-thursdays/ ) :

During an industry conference last year, NBA commissioner Adam Silver admit=
ted he was =E2=80=9Cfascinated=E2=80=9D with the job Amazon Prime Video is =
doing with =E2=80=9CThursday Night Football=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 the ratings-=
challenged NFL package from which longtime broadcast partners like Fox Spor=
ts and CBS Sports had walked away. With =E2=80=9CTNF=E2=80=9D averaging a l=
inear TV-like 12.9 million viewers year to date this season, Amazon wants t=
o create an exclusive night of streaming NBA action, sources told Front Off=
ice Sports.

According to sources, after agreeing to pay $1 billion yearly for =E2=80=9C=
TNF=E2=80=9D through 2033, the eCommerce giant is eying an NBA game package=
 on Tuesday or Thursday nights. The goal: create the NBA=E2=80=99s version =
of =E2=80=9CTNF,=E2=80=9D said sources. According to sources, the NBA is al=
so intrigued by Amazon=E2=80=99s ability to draw an audience seven years yo=
unger than the NFL=E2=80=99s legacy TV partners.

Let=E2=80=99s be clear: what the NBA is looking for is money first and fore=
most. That noted, Amazon does strike me as the most likely partner amongst =
the tech companies. What makes the service different from other streaming a=
lternatives is that Prime already has around 167 million U.S. subscribers, =
substantially more than cable. This means that the NBA would serve as churn=
 mitigation for a larger bundle offering already at scale; given that the N=
BA is substantially less popular than the NFL =E2=80=94 regular season game=
s averaged 1.6 million viewers =E2=80=94 that seems like a more viable busi=
ness case than believing the league will drive subscribers for a smaller se=
rvice like Apple TV+.

Still, it=E2=80=99s hard to see the numbers getting as high as the NBA woul=
d like: $1 billion for 12 million weekly NFL viewers is less than ESPN pays=
 for a much smaller audience ($1.4 billion currently), for a much different=
 product that, unlike cable, doesn=E2=80=99t have hours of inventory that n=
eed to be filled on weeknights in February.

Jon Stewart vs. Apple
---------------------

From the New York Times ( https://www.nytimes.com/2023/10/19/business/media=
/jon-stewart-the-problem-ends.html ) :

Jon Stewart=E2=80=99s show on Apple=E2=80=99s streaming service is abruptly=
 coming to an end, according to several people with knowledge of the decisi=
on, the result of creative differences between the tech giant and the forme=
r =E2=80=9CDaily Show=E2=80=9D host=E2=80=A6Mr. Stewart and Apple executive=
s had disagreements over some of the topics and guests on =E2=80=9CThe Prob=
lem,=E2=80=9D two of the people said. Mr. Stewart told members of his staff=
 on Thursday that potential show topics related to China and artificial int=
elligence were causing concern among Apple executives, a person with knowle=
dge of the meeting said. As the 2024 presidential campaign begins to heat u=
p, there was potential for further creative disagreements, one of the peopl=
e said.

We discussed this topic on today=E2=80=99s Dithering ( https://dithering.fm=
/ ) (link below!), so I=E2=80=99ll keep this short.

First off, I find it hard to believe that Stewart=E2=80=99s coverage of Chi=
na wasn=E2=80=99t negotiated before he signed on with Apple in the first pl=
ace. That doesn=E2=80=99t make it ok that world-spanning tech companies inc=
reasingly have editorial control over our media ecosystem =E2=80=94 geograp=
hically-constrained cable companies don=E2=80=99t seem so bad in this light=
! =E2=80=94 but rather I would be surprised if this was some sort of unexpe=
cted issue.

What seems more likely to me is that the show was a flop, and not just beca=
use I=E2=80=99ve heard it was much less compelling than Stewart=E2=80=99s o=
ld Daily Show. Rather, the entire concept of a talk show seems much more su=
ited to linear TV: news drives daily content, which you turn on because it =
is there, or place in the background; streaming, on the other hand, is all =
about intentionality, and it=E2=80=99s a pretty heavy lift to get someone t=
o purposely seek out a news-related show on a relatively new streaming serv=
ice that isn=E2=80=99t super-fresh and yet also has an expiration date. The=
 entire concept seems flawed.

This seems pertinent to the NBA=E2=80=99s hopes above: the NBA=E2=80=99s gr=
eatest value has always been that it fills out the schedule when football i=
sn=E2=80=99t on; in that regard it is similar to something like the Daily S=
how that both fills time and mitigates some small amount of churn, enabling=
 affiliate fees to go up. On streaming, though, the =E2=80=9Cfiller content=
=E2=80=9D aspect is different: filler content matters, but it needs to be c=
ontent that is evergreen; filler content on linear TV, on the other hand, n=
eeds to fill a specific time slot. Both talk shows and live sports are much=
 better suited to the latter.

That does still leave the churn mitigation aspects I noted above, and the N=
BA=E2=80=99s schedule offset relative to the NFL could help Amazon lock in =
sports fans and perhaps lay the foundation to aggregate sports more broadly=
